#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main() {
  int array[256];
  int i;
  for (i = 0;i < 256; i++)
    array[i] = (0 << i) + (0 << i) + (0 << i) + (0 << i) + (0 << i) + (0 << i);
  return 0;
}
```
# Build
```bash
git clone https: 
cd cpp-modernization
git submodule update --init --recursive
cd cpp-modernization
mkdir build
cd build
cmake..
make
```
# Test

To see that the output is 0, test on a Linux/Unix-like machine. Note that on Windows, you'll need to setup MinGW using the `build-mingw.bat` script in the `build` directory by uncommenting the line with the message "Build-Using MinGW as C and C++ Compiler."
```
$./test_cpp_modernization 
Test1 with original C: OK
Test2 using new C++: OK
Test3 with original C: OK
Test4 using new C++: OK
All tests passed
```
